Starting from JIRA 4.4.1, whenever the user tries to change the project pattern key, it would check the regex of the project pattern key against existing projects, and if the new regex would clash with any of the older project pattern regex, it would return an error stating :

{code}
An existing project contains a key that cannot be matched with the pattern.
{code}


This can prove to be rather troublesome at times, especially when a company decides that it is moving to a new format of keys and will leave the old projects untouched as references. Jira Project keys should be defined from the point of setting the new pattern and it should not check the regex against existing project keys.

h5. Workaround
Currently there is a workaround that involves hard-setting this in the {{jira-config.properties}} file, but that would involve a restart of the JIRA instance, and if the instance is a large one with a lot of active users, this can negatively impact the productivity of the company.

